prompt: Explain in three sentences what was the Reichrat of the Weimar Republic.
text: The Reichrat, also known as the Reichstag's Permanent Committee or the Permanent Council of the German Reichstag, was an important legislative body in the Weimar Republic of Germany between 1919 and 1933. Its primary function was to prepare and oversee the work of the plenary sessions of the Reichstag by drafting and revising bills, conducting preliminary debates, and organizing committees to investigate specific issues. The Reichrat was composed of members elected by the Reichstag and represented all political parties proportionally to their representation in the parliament.
